s, gambling banned, weapons locked down."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"Wounded at Williamsburg, a general by summer","body":"The 5th Michigan absorbed heavy losses at Williamsburg — where Terry was wounded — and at Seven Pines; by mid-July 1862 he wore a brigadier’s star. The next spring Longstreet besieged his brigade at Suffolk."},{"number":3,"category":"military","header":"He talked his own general into retreating","body":"At Baltimore Cross Roads in July 1863, within striking distance of Richmond, Terry fed General Keyes’s fears of Confederates massing in their rear — helping persuade him to retreat. Dix and Keyes lost their commands; Terry ended the war garrisoning the Johnson’s Island prison camp, superseded and idle by May 1864."}],"slug":"henry-terry-1812"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}